		<div class=3D"wp-block-image is-style-default">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-large"><a href=3D"https://i0.wp.com/www.c=
ompoundchem.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/Mohs-Hardness-Scale.png?ssl=3D1"=
 target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"nofollow"><img data-recalc-dims=3D"1" fetchpriori=
ty=3D"high" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1024" height=3D"724" src=3D"https:/=
/i0.wp.com/www.compoundchem.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/Mohs-Hardness-Sc=
ale.png?resize=3D1024%2C724&amp;ssl=3D1" alt=3D"Infographic on the Mohs Min=
eral Hardness Scale. The graphic shows the scale, which runs from 0-10, and=
 also highlights a number of minerals with their point on the scale. Key re=
ference minerals for each point on the scale are also shown: 1 =3D talc, 2 =
=3D gypsum, 3 =3D calcite, 4 =3D fluorite, 5 =3D apatite, 6 =3D feldspar, 7=
 =3D quartz, 8 =3D topaz, 9 =3D corundum, 10 =3D diamond." class=3D"wp-imag=
e-32657"></a><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">Click to enlarge</fig=
caption></figure></div>


<p>Diamond is commonly known to be the hardest material, but how do other m=
inerals compare with each other? That=E2=80=99s the question the Mohs hardn=
ess scale, introduced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Friedrich=
_Mohs" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"nofollow">Friedrich Mohs</a> in 1812, aims =
to answer. This graphic looks at his scale and where different minerals and=
 other substances appear on it.</p>



<span id=3D"more-32656"></span>



<p>Mohs=E2=80=99 scale is a simple way of comparing the hardness of differe=
nt minerals. The scale is built on comparisons =E2=80=94 a mineral that scr=
atches another is designated as having a higher value for hardness. These v=
alues are essentially a giant ranking system, in that they=E2=80=99re all r=
elative. There=E2=80=99s no fixed value of hardness between the different n=
umbers in the scale =E2=80=94 in fact, diamond at 10 is several times harde=
r than corundum at 9, but corundum is only around twice as hard as topaz at=
 8.</p>



<p>You=E2=80=99d be forgiven for wondering, given this variability between =
points on the scale, what its use is. It=E2=80=99s particularly useful for =
geologists in the field who can use known reference materials or minerals t=
o scratch unknown minerals and estimate where on the scale they sit, aiding=
 their identification. </p>



<p>Some of the additional items I=E2=80=99ve included on the scale in the g=
raphic are relevant to the reference materials geologists may use =E2=80=94=
 for example, fingernails, copper coins, steel knives, and ceramic streak p=
lates. I=E2=80=99ve also included some other non-mineral substances on the =
scale for reference, such as some common metals and some other materials no=
ted for their high hardness, like tungsten carbide.</p>



<p>Is diamond really the hardest material known? In terms of naturally-occu=
rring substances, the answer appears to be yes, though lab-grown materials =
are providing potential challengers, <a href=3D"https://www.cam.ac.uk/resea=
rch/discussion/opinion-harder-than-diamond-have-scientists-really-found-som=
ething-tougher-than-natures-invincible" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"nofollow">=
as this article summarises</a>.</p>



<p>I=E2=80=99ll finish by concluding that I=E2=80=99m not a geologist, and =
this isn=E2=80=99t intended to be a comprehensive chart =E2=80=94 there are=
 many more minerals out there than it was possible to include on it! Howeve=
r, I=E2=80=99ve tried to include a representative spread of minerals. Shout=
 in the comments if you=E2=80=99ve noted any glaring omissions!</p>



